# TypeScript Decorators

Decorators are **annotations that wrap a class, method, property, or parameter with additional behaviour**. The mental model: a decorator is a higher-order function applied at class definition time. When the file is first loaded, the decorator runs — before any instances are created.

```
Decorator execution order:

@Controller('/users')           ← class decorator — runs last (outermost)
class UserController {

  @Get('/:id')                  ← method decorator — runs per method
  @Validate(UserSchema)         ← stacked decorators run bottom-up
  getUser(@Param('id') id: string) {
    //      ↑ parameter decorator — runs first (innermost)
  }
}

Runtime order (bottom to top):
  1. @Param('id')      — parameter decorator for 'id'
  2. @Validate         — method decorator
  3. @Get('/:id')      — method decorator
  4. @Controller       — class decorator
```

## Enabling Decorators

```json
// tsconfig.json — decorators are NOT enabled by default
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "experimentalDecorators": true,
    "emitDecoratorMetadata": true  // needed for reflect-metadata (Angular/NestJS)
  }
}
```

## Class Decorators

A class decorator receives the constructor and can return a new constructor or modify the existing one.

```ts
// Simple logging decorator
function Logged(target: Function) {
  console.log(`Class defined: ${target.name}`);
}

@Logged
class MyService {}  // Logs 'Class defined: MyService' when file loads

// Decorator factory — returns the actual decorator, accepts config
function Injectable(scope: 'singleton' | 'transient' = 'singleton') {
  return function(target: Function) {
    Reflect.defineMetadata('scope', scope, target);
  };
}

@Injectable('transient')
class UserService {}
```

## Method Decorators

Method decorators receive `(target, propertyKey, descriptor)`. They can replace or wrap the method.

```ts
function Bind(
  target: any,
  propertyKey: string,
  descriptor: PropertyDescriptor
): PropertyDescriptor {
  // Wrap with auto-bind so 'this' is always correct:
  const original = descriptor.value;
  return {
    ...descriptor,
    get() {
      return original.bind(this);
    },
  };
}

class Button {
  label = 'Click me';

  @Bind
  handleClick() {
    console.log(this.label);  // 'this' always refers to Button instance
  }
}

// Timing decorator:
function Timed(target: any, name: string, desc: PropertyDescriptor) {
  const original = desc.value;
  desc.value = function(...args: any[]) {
    const start = Date.now();
    const result = original.apply(this, args);
    console.log(`${name} took ${Date.now() - start}ms`);
    return result;
  };
  return desc;
}
```

## Property Decorators

```ts
function MinLength(min: number) {
  return function(target: any, propertyKey: string) {
    // Store validation metadata on the class prototype
    const rules = Reflect.getMetadata('validations', target) || [];
    rules.push({ property: propertyKey, type: 'minLength', value: min });
    Reflect.defineMetadata('validations', rules, target);
  };
}

class User {
  @MinLength(3)
  name: string = '';  // validation rule is stored in metadata
}
```

## Parameter Decorators

```ts
function Param(key: string) {
  return function(target: any, methodName: string, paramIndex: number) {
    // Record which parameter index corresponds to which route param key
    const metadata = Reflect.getMetadata('params', target, methodName) || [];
    metadata[paramIndex] = key;
    Reflect.defineMetadata('params', metadata, target, methodName);
  };
}

class UserController {
  getUser(@Param('id') id: string, @Param('version') v: string) {
    // At runtime: framework reads metadata to extract id and v from request
  }
}
```

## Decorator Factories vs Direct Decorators

```
Direct decorator:           Decorator factory:

@Logged                     @Injectable('singleton')
class Foo {}                class Bar {}

  ↓                               ↓
LoggedDecorator(Foo)        Injectable('singleton')(Bar)
                                ↑
                           factory called first,
                           returns the actual decorator
```

```ts
// Direct — no config
function Logged(target: Function) { /* ... */ }
@Logged class Foo {}

// Factory — with config
function Log(level: 'info'|'warn') {
  return (target: Function) => { /* use level */ };
}
@Log('warn') class Bar {}
```

## reflect-metadata

Angular and NestJS use `reflect-metadata` to store and retrieve type and parameter info at runtime:

```ts
import 'reflect-metadata';

// emitDecoratorMetadata: true makes TypeScript emit:
// Reflect.metadata('design:type', String) for properties
// Reflect.metadata('design:paramtypes', [String, Number]) for constructors

@Injectable()
class UserService {
  constructor(
    private db: DatabaseService,   // type info emitted as metadata
    private logger: LoggerService
  ) {}
}
// NestJS reads 'design:paramtypes' to auto-inject db and logger
```

## Decorator Composition Cheatsheet

| Decorator type | Target | Args | Common use |
|---|---|---|---|
| Class | Constructor function | target | @Injectable, @Component |
| Method | Prototype + descriptor | target, key, descriptor | @Get, @Timed, @Bind |
| Accessor | Same as method | target, key, descriptor | @Computed |
| Property | Prototype | target, key | @Column, @MinLength |
| Parameter | Prototype, method name, index | target, key, index | @Param, @Body, @Query |

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting `experimentalDecorators: true` in tsconfig — decorators will error without it
- Stacked decorators execute bottom-up — order matters for composition
- Decorators on class properties run at class definition, not at instance creation — the property value doesn't exist yet
- `emitDecoratorMetadata` requires `reflect-metadata` to be imported somewhere in your entry point
- `design:type` metadata gives you the TypeScript type as a JavaScript constructor — erased generics appear as `Object`

